Pt is a 26 yo M with a documented allergy to Amoxicillin (rxn: Rash; severity: Not Specified; since 01/19/2018). On 04/08/21, pt presented to clinic for immunization. At 0834, pt was administered COVID-19 J&J (Janssen) Vaccine 0.5 mL in left deltoid (Lot #207A21A; Exp: 6/23/2021; NDC #59676-580-15). After injection, pt became diaphoretic and dizzy. Pt reported similar reaction with blood draws. Pt was placed in supine position, given water and ice packs were applied to his neck. Pt evaluated by MD with no new orders given. After 10 minutes of observation, pt reported symptom resolution and return to baseline. Vitals assessed as BP: 126/81, P: 77, O2 sats: 97%. Pt discharged in stable condition.

26 2021-04-09 dizziness Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine EUA I received the Janssen vaccine in my upper-left arm at 3:00 PM on Apri... Read more
Close
Janssen COVID-19 Vaccine EUA I received the Janssen vaccine in my upper-left arm at 3:00 PM on April 5, 2021, at a public health clinic (I think that's the proper term for the site) established in a mall. After about ten minutes, during the scheduled waiting period, I began to feel lightheaded; I can best compare the feeling to that of being tipsy after a glass or two of wine. I waited another twenty minutes at the site to see if the feeling worsened, and when it didn't, I left without telling anyone how I felt. During the drive home, however, I continued to feel lightheaded during the drive home and worried that it might be affecting my driving. After I got home without incident, the feeling persisted for a few hours and ceased that evening. Since then, I have experienced nothing but what I think are standard post-vaccination symptoms (fatigue, muscle aches, slight brain fog, swollen lymph nodes?not unlike the sensations of recovering from a modest cold). I nevertheless want to report the lightheadedness because it appears (based on news reports) that it is an unusual reaction to the vaccine. I want to make sure that my experience is recorded, even though I do not believe that I require further medical attention.

The patient was nervous prior to vaccine and had a needle phobia. About 5 minutes post-vaccine, the patient stated he was not feeling well and feeling warm and sweaty. The pharmacy staff provided the patient with water and an ice pack. The patient stated he was feeling faint. The patient fainted for about 20 seconds and then became conscious again. The patient didn't have any injuries and didn't fall down. The patient was okay and he laid down and elevated his feet on a chair. He was still slightly faint and requested that he be checked out. The EMT arrived and they took his vitals and checked him. By the time the EMT arrived, he was beginning to feel better and had sat up and drinking water. There were no further issues. The EMT stated he was good to head home. We followed up with patient and the patient was feeling good with no further issues.

26 2021-04-15 dizziness pt reported feeling lightheaded, drank juice, ate, cool cloth to back of neck
26 2021-04-18 dizziness I received the J&J vaccine at 10:00am on March 18, 2021 at the Community Center. By about 5:00pm, I ... Read more
Close
I received the J&J vaccine at 10:00am on March 18, 2021 at the Community Center. By about 5:00pm, I started to feel minor flu-like symptoms, but as the night progressed it got significantly worse. Around 8-9pm, I was bedridden with the worst chills/shaking I've ever experienced in my life. Around 9:30-10:00pm, I was filling water at my sink and projectile vomitted multiple times into the sink and could not make it to the bathroom. Subsequently, I ate a bagel and drank lots of water, knowing my vomitting could make me dehydrated. Throughout the night, I was awake and shaking, and drank and filled my water bottle repeatedly. At 8:00am, I was filling my water, and without my knowledge of awareness, fainted on my kitchen floor, dropping the Brita filter and likely hitting my head. My roommate heard the commotion and saw me passed out in our kitchen. He tried to wake me up and I phased in, but then subsequently phased out again 20-30 seconds later as I was trying to stand and likely hit my head again. My roommate eventually got me over to our couch and called EMTs. Upon their arrival, EMTs checked my pulse, which was fine, and saw an open laceration on the back of my head, so they took me to Hospital to access the Trauma Center. On the way, I threw up repeatedly and was very lightheaded. Upon my arrival at Hospital, I was checked for any neck bone breaks, given an IV, a CT scan, an EKG, and staples were placed in the back of my head to heal the laceration. After my release, I was bedridden for 2-3 days and required a daily nap during work (1-2) hours for the next 1 1/2 to 2 weeks. For a while, everything was fine, but recently during the first two weeks of April, it has become apparent that my head is foggy and reacts to changes in the weather, which leads me to believe that I likely banged my head pretty good when I fainted those two times.
26 2021-04-20 dizziness BLOOD SUGAR WAS 9; BLOOD PRESSURE 132/95; NAUSEA; PAIN IN BACK OF HEAD; DIZZINESS; LOSS OF CONSCIOUS... Read more

BLOOD SUGAR WAS 9; BLOOD PRESSURE 132/95; NAUSEA; PAIN IN BACK OF HEAD; DIZZINESS; LOSS OF CONSCIOUSNESS; This spontaneous report received from a physician concerned a 26 year old male. The patient's weight was 245 pounds, and height was 172.7 centimeters. The patient had no known allergies and had no chronic medical history. The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of administration was not reported, batch number: 202A21A and expiry: unknown) dose was not reported, 1 total, administered on left deltoid on 08-APR-2021 for prophylactic vaccination. No concomitant medications were reported. On 09-APR-2021, the patient complained of dizziness, nausea and pain in back of his head. Once the nurse arrived at the cell, the patient was on the floor with loss of consciousness. He was placed on a stretcher following which he regained consciousness. His vitals signs (unspecified) were stable, blood sugar was 9 (unit not provided), blood pressure was 132/95 (unit not provided) and respiratory rate was at 18 (unit not provided) (NR: not provided for all tests). The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient recovered from loss of consciousness on APR-2021, had not recovered from dizziness, nausea, and pain in back of head, and the outcome of blood sugar was 9 and blood pressure 132/95 was not reported. This report was serious (Other Medically Important Condition).; Sender's Comments: V0-20210420193- Covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s-loss of consciousness. This event is considered unassessable. The event has a compatible/suggestive temporal relationship, is unlabeled, and has unknown scientific plausibility. There is no information on any other factors potentially associated with the event.

I consider myself a pretty healthy guy with a healthy lifestyle. I did not feel the need to go to the ER quite yet, but I did have a friend come over to monitor me. 31 2021-05-09 fall At 23:15 (7 hours after the dose) I started to get cold while under my blankets trying to sleep. My ... Read more
Close
At 23:15 (7 hours after the dose) I started to get cold while under my blankets trying to sleep. My teeth began chattering as I started to shiver. I got up out of bed to put on a sweater. With each step I took towards the sweater my body started to fully shiver and contract. After about 4 or 5 steps I could no longer move and I fell over. I started having full body spasms and full contractions. I felt like I pulled every muscle in my body trying to relax and fight the contractions. It felt like I was being tasered for about 10-15 minutes. Once I had the strength to grab my sweater I slipped it on. As my body warmed up these contraction subsided. By 01:00 (9 hours after dose) my body temperature had spiked. I didn't have a thermometer to check my temperature but I wouldn't be surprised if I spiked a fever. I placed a wet cloth on the back of my neck, forehead and chest to cool down. At 06:00 (14 hours after dose) I took a cold shower to further drop my body's temperature. It felt like a full body sun burn where you just radiate heat. I was hot everywhere. At 08:00 (16 hours after dose) I took three (3) 500mg ibuprofen to help fight a nagging headache. I did not have much appetite for food. I regularly eat breakfast in the morning (bowl of cereal). From 09:00 to 12:00 (17-20 hours after dose) I felt groggy. Did not seem or act like myself. Was very tired from the lack of sleep the night prior. Seemed very fatigued. Around 13:00 (21 hours after dose) I took a 45-60 minute nap. Woke up feeling much better. I would say most / if not all symptoms subsided after 22-24 hours.

Roughly three hours after getting the shot I was very cold and developed a fever of 102.8. I vomited that night. I took an ibuprofen to help reduce the fever then slept. For the next six days I had an on again and off again low grade fever and was nauseas most of the time. Sometime during those 6 days I developed intermitted tingling in my left hand, primarily by index finger. This continues to today happening roughly once a day. On rare occasion my right had will do the same thing but that is far less often. I never had tingling in either hand prior to my vaccine. I also developed heartburn occurring roughly 1-2 times a day. Prior to the vaccine I rarely (1-2 times a year) had heartburn and I have not changed anything about my diet or lifestyle since my vaccine. Occasionally my head feels "foggy" as well and this began sometime after the vaccine but I can't recall exactly when it started. It's not a headache, more of a slight lightheaded, dull feeling. I had none of these symptoms with any regularity until I was administered the vaccine.

He relayed that he had passed out from vaccinations in the past as a child. He affirms lightheadedness and nausea. He denies chest pain, difficulty breathing, swelling of the face/lips/tongue/throat, skin rash/itching, cramping abdominal pain, and vomiting. Exam (update as needed): GEN: Upon arrival, patient unconscious and not responsive to stimuli HEAD: NCAT EYES: pupils unreactive and mydriatic ENT: Ears normal, Nose normal, OP normal, no evidence of angioedema NECK: Supple, without LAD. EMS arrived and an EKG and BGL were performed, both of which were normal. Vital signs were stable. Instructed patient to consult their PCP regarding the post-vaccination reaction. Patient instructed to go to emergency department should they develop chest pain, difficulty breathing, swelling of the face/lips/mouth/tongue/throat, or cramping abdominal pain with nausea/vomiting, as these are signs of possible anaphylaxis that requires immediate intervention. Pt. requested and received the J&J / Jansen COVID 19 vaccination yesterday at 1317. While he was being monitored for any adverse reactions, Pt. asked if lightheadedness was a side effect of the shot. Writer advised that it could be and that everyone is different. Writer asked if he would like some water, and he declined. Pt. was advised to remove his mask so he could breathe better. Writer took his pulse while I gathered information. It was 96. Pt. reported that he did eat lunch, is drinking plenty of water and fluids. He relayed he is keeping food down and not having any other issues. Pt. is currently on opiate withdrawal protocol. Writer asked about his breathing and his chest. Pt. relayed he was not having difficulty breathing and denied any chest pain at all. Writer spoke with the Deputy to be sure that we kept an eye on him for a bit longer after his 15 minutes while he was in his cell, due to his lightheadedness. Pt. was talking with writer, answering questions with ease. Pt. was not diaphoretic and did have good color. His pulse was checked again, and it was 84. When he stood, pt.'s knees buckled, and he knelt to the ground. Writer helped pt. to lay down. It was a smooth transition, and he had no injuries to his head or body. Pt. had what appeared to be a short spell where his body completely tensed for a few seconds, then he relaxed. He was having a hard time keeping his eyes open, but when prompted, was able to open his eyes. The Deputy standing by was asked to call for the Public Health Nurses, who had moved on to the next POD to continue vaccinating. Once on the scene, pt.'s blood pressure was obtained. 142/80. His pulse was 82. During this time, it appeared that the tensing episodes became more frequent and a bit more severe. They were happening approximately every 30 seconds, and lasting between 5 and 10 seconds. EMS was activated at approximately 1340. Pt. was awake during these episodes, and communicated with the nurses attending to him. While attending to pt. and waiting for EMS, it was at that time that pt. admitted that this was not the first time this had happened. He admitted that about a week ago, the same thing happened. When that new information was explored, pt. reported that his wife thought he had "Serotonin Syndrome". Writer asked what meds he was taking on the outside and he reported that he only takes methadone form the clinic. He denied any other medications or street drug usage. He does not take any mental health medications at our facility. Collectively, the nurses that attended to him after this episode agreed that this is an isolated incident and not related to receiving the COVID vaccine. EMS arrived at approximately 1347, and report was given. He was transported to the hospital for evaluation. Pt. was returned from the hospital at approximately 1600. The Officer that accompanied him reported to facility that the hospital also believed this was an isolated incident, most likely related to withdrawals. They did not believe that receiving the vaccine was a factor in today's events. Labs were drawn at the hospital, and were all WNL. Once back in custody, writer spoke briefly with pt.. He was feeling much better, and was sent back to his cell without further incident.

Patient reported light-headedness approximately 15 minutes after vaccination. He said it was mild, but felt like when he doesn't eat and gets light-headed. I asked patient to remain seated and got him some water. He drank the water and after approximately 5 minutes said he felt fine. Reported no dizziness or light-headedness. I asked him if he would like to remain in observation for longer, but patient said he was ready to go home and repeated that he felt fine. He said that he would call if he had any questions or concerns.
